Site Upgrade/Announcements
This is the second time writing this because my current system is kinda stupid, and it made me lose two posts that I wrote, so if this seems hastily written, that's why.

In the future, there are going to be some changes coming to the website. Here they are:
<ol>
<li>I plan to be switching my current system of writing/publishing posts. The website will stay the same, and theoretically there should be no noticable difference for the reader. Here's a technical explanation: I currently use Python to write to files and convert them to HTML for the website and they get uploaded to GitHub in the public repository that everyone can see. While I programmed everything and I am proud of it, there are several things that I might still need to do (like saving posts when you're done so you don't have to rewrite them), but I have a better way now that I am going to do this. While I could migrate over to Wordpress, I don't want to. I like complete control over my website. What I will be doing is moving all my data over to Google Firebase, which is a live updating database system that works with JavaScript and web stuff. And migrating to Firebase leads into my second annoucement:</li>
<li>I will be making an effort to have multiple authors on the website. I know several members of my youth group write stuff down, and since I am gifted with the technical knowledge that I have, I might as well not keep it all for myself and share it to make something that we can all use. I will be rebranding a little bit, and call it BibleThoughts instead of just Teen Bible Thoughts. Why? I honestly don't know. I think it's more because I'm getting older, so I want to still be a part of it and keep this alive, but I might as well rebrand now while I'm making these changes. But multiple authors. It's something I've wanted to do for a while, but now I have all the tools to do it. Now just to do it...</li>
<li>My final announcement will be good for those who view my page on their phone. I do know that this site isn't very mobile friendly, and that's why I want to make a mobile friendly version, and also make it so that you can add it as an app on your phone to view at any time. It will still be a website, which has it's limitations as a website, but I already am working on it for iOS, and hopefully will figure it out for Android. I am working on this now, so this will probably be the first update to come out. I want to get this done so I can slot the Firebase changes right in for the new layout for mobile.</li></ol>

I am excited for these changes, and will probably get working on them when summer break starts (either when I am 'studying for finals', or when I am lying in bed in pain from getting my only 3 wisdom teeth removed. I already know most of what needs to be done, but I just need to do it. I'm excited!!!

God's Presence
I actually shouldn't be on my laptop right now, but I was watching a sermon on the Hillsong Channel, and it made me think of this post, so I think my mom can excuse it this time.

Anyways, I was watching a sermon on the Hillsong Channel because it was on and it gave me a reason to stay up. I wasn't paying too much attention to the main topic of the sermon, but when I payed attention, the preacher was talking about entering the presence of God. He said that there were three ways to enter into the presense of God, and he said the first one was through worship. He gave a few passeges from Psalms, but I was already out of it. Near the end of his sermon, I started thinking. I guess God kind of dropped something onto me, and I realize why God seems to move when we worship.

According to the Merriam-Webster dictionary, worship is defined as "extravagant respect or admiration for or devotion to an object of esteem". It's like in Britian when the Queen walks in, everyone might kneel or show some sign of respect for her. People even refer to her as "Your Highness". I realized that when we worship, this is exactly what we do for the Lord. We put the Lord's status above our own, and give him praises for how good He is and everything He is. Whenever you enter a room where believers are praising and lifting up Jesus' name, you can tell when the Lord's presense is manifested. You can tell that He is there.

But it's all because we set our own status and our own ego aside for a moment to lift up the Lord. That's why it doesn't matter if you're on the worship team, if you're the one who wrote the lyrics to the powerful worship song, and it doesn't even matter if you are musically (or vocally) gifted. As long as you are lifting up the Lord over yourself, His presence can come and be manifested. In Romans 12:1, Paul says to "be a living sacrifice", and that "This is truly the way to worship Him". It doesn't say "sing with the voice of an angel - and this is truly acceptable worship", but it says about laying ourselves down, and putting ourselves aside.

Even though I've been told this and understand it, I still struggle with this. But from Adam and Eve, when humanity decided that we were going to elevate ourselves over what God says, we gave sin a foot in the door, and something that isn't God entered. But when we lay our lives down, we push that out the door, and let God enter in.

I hope this encourages people, and I hope this post benefits us all (and pray that my mom doesn't get too mad for me being on my laptop when I shouldn't be).

Makeup
A common thing in the present times is for women to wear makeup. As a guy, I don't know or understand makeup, but I know that some people think they need it. Some people will see little faults in their skin or think they need a little extra help on their appearance to look good enough to go out in public.

But spiritually, some people also think they need makeup. Some people see their own little faults abnd feel they need to cover them up before they can come before the Lord. I have two things to say on that.

Matthew 11:28 says: "Then Jesus said, 'Come to me, all of you who are weary and carry heavy burdens, and I will give you rest.'"

Jesus says here that when you come to Him with all your issues, He will give you rest. He doesn't say to mask your faults and you will find rest, but He says to be transparent, an to come to Him with your faults.

Also, 2 Corinthians 13:4 says: "Although he was crucified in weakness, he now lives by the power of Go. We, too, are weak, just as Christ was, but when we deal with you we will be alive with him and and will have God's power."

In ourselves, we are weak. But in Christ, we have power. This very statement shows that Christ is bigger than us in everything. So when we think we have a problem, when we look at it though Christ's perspective, that problem is so small that it might as well not exist.

When you are being fed lies by the enemy, that you are not "Holy and blameless" (Colossians 1:22), look at your issues through the One who calls you Holy an blameless, who wipes clean all faults. And because of Him, you don't need any 'spiritual makeup' to come before the Lord.

Grow Up
I want to start this post by saying the Holy Spirit spoke to me through my pastor tonight, in a way that wasn't too relivant to his message. So credit goes to my pastor and the Holy Spirit for this one.

Recently, growing up is starting to hit me hard. Let's look at how grown up I am. I will get my full license in less than a month, I will be an adult in around 6 months, I will be a senior in high school this year, and starting college the next. To me, the shock of growing up is setting in, and I don't really like it. It hurts to know that I will have to be responsible for myself, and will sort of be shoved into the real world to make decisions on my own. It's a reality that I'm facing, and I'm not accepting it too well. I don't want to grow up. I want to stay young.

God spoke to me tonight, and came at me like the Holy Spirit swung a baseball bat at my face with 'Grow up!' written all over it. At first it was like 'Woah, I am really putting off growing up', but then I realized what God was actually speaking to me. I am sort of sad to start my senior year, because I have tough classes, and I want to just continue to enjoy summer and not have the stress of assignments, essays, and whatnot. But as some may know, I am the leader of the Bible Club in our school. And me over here keeps saying that I don't want to start this school year, is sort of like saying to God, 'Hey, there's some stuff in store for this school this year, but you need to wait until my terms to start moving.' I'm sure more mature Christians will see this and be like 'Caleb, don't work against God, because you're looking for a rough time.' I know most of the Bible stories, and one in particular is where Pharaoh's heart was hardened to the Lord (read through Exodous 8-14). So I understand moving against God is a bad idea.

Instead of trying to swim against the tide of life (I will get picked up and carried away anyways weather I like it or not), I need to lift up my feet and surrender to the current, and just trust in God to take control of the tides. Trust Him with leading me through my early adult years, trust Him with my grades this year, trust Him to lead me to the college that His Plan wants me to go to, trust Him to guide me through college, and just trust His Plan for my life, and know that He's in control, and that no matter what, "He will neither fail you nor abandon you" (Deuteronomy 31:6 NLT).']}
